<DOC><DOCNO> AP890408-0106 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-08-89 1810EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-08 0478</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0495</SECOND><HEAD>Flooding Threatens North Dakota; Snow in North Carolina</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   More than a foot of snow blanketed the North Carolina mountainsSaturday while authorities in North Dakota rushed to complete aseries of dikes to protect Fargo from the rising Red River.   Scorching temperatures continued in California, but the heat wasexpected to break Sunday with temperatures in most coastaldistricts back down to the 70s and 80s.   Across the continent, up to 14 inches of snow have accumulatedin Macon County, N.C., and snow also was falling in Maine, NewHampshire, and in the Rockies.   Flood warnings were reported in Baton Rouge, La., where theMississippi River was 4 feet below flood stage, and throughout therest of the South. Flooding also threatened in New England, acrossNorth Dakota and Minnesota and in Indiana, Illinois and Ohio.   Along the Red River, residents of Fargo and neighboringMoorhead, Minn., readied for the flood-swollen river's predictedcrest on Monday, 19 feet above flood stage.   Dean Peterson, a spokesman for the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers,said work on an extensive network of dikes was virtually completed.   ``Right now, we're pretty much done ... if everything maintainsthe way it is,'' Peterson said Saturday.   There were scattered rainshowers from northern Arkansas tonorthern Illinois, from the central Gulf states to the lower GreatLakes region, and from Georgia to Virginia.   Heavier rainfall totals for the six-hour period ending at 2 p.m.EDT included half an inch at Chattanooga, Tn., .51 inch atMarietta, Ga., and a third of an inch at Huntsville, Ala.   Heavier snowfall totals for the six-hour period ending at 2 p.m.EDT included three inches at Eastport, Maine, and one inch at MountWashington, N.H.   Dry weather prevailed across the rest of the nation, with sunnyskies over southern and central Texas and much of the Southwest.   Temperatures soared into the 90s in south Texas, while readingsdropped into the teens in northern Minnesota, Wisconsin and upperMichigan.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 13degrees at International Falls, Minn., to 106 degrees at PalmSprings, Calif.   Sunday's forecast called for snow from Wyoming through easternColorado to Missouri, over the Great Lakes region and northern NewEngland. Showers and a few thunderstorms were expected to extendfrom the Texas Panhandle to Arkansas, with fair to partly sunnyskies over the rest of the nation and windy conditions in themid-Atlantic Coast region.   High temperatures were expected in the 30s and upper 20s fromthe northern and central Plains to New England; above 70 degreesfrom California and western Oregon through southern and centralTexas to Florida and southern Georgia; in the 80s across theFlorida peninsula, from central California to south central Texas;in the 90s or above 100 degrees in Southern California and southernArizona.</TEXT></DOC>